english:
  title: The Capital
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Willows bend and wave—sending me homeward with their grace.
    This journey proves better than the last time I returned.
    Though the landscape remains indifferent to my plight,
    The human heart naturally harbors both joy and sorrow.

    To ride hard viewing blossoms—such pleasures come to me,
    Yet the one thrown from his donkey, lost in the fields—who knows his name?
    The wines of Song-do must be ripening now.
    I'll return and lose myself in drink, ready to compose wild verses.

    One curve of sand-bank beside the jade-green creek,
    East of the palace grounds, west of the purple gate.
    My earnest words were plain—criticism cuts deeply indeed.
    Slow to grasp the truth, my own thoughts grow ever dimmer.

    Before the window, the green parasol tree—wind whispers soft and fine.
    On the stone steps, red peonies trembling as rain falls, pittering and pattering.
    Though I grow old, could youth alone have justified my service?
    Yet here I am, drafting another memorial as dusk descends.
  footnotes:
    - Song-do (송도) refers to Kaesong, the capital of Goryeo, suggesting the speaker is returning from the royal capital.
    - The image of being thrown from one's donkey suggests losing one's position or favor at court.
    - The final lines reference the speaker's ongoing role in government—"drafting another memorial" suggests preparing advice or remonstrance for the throne, a duty that weighs on him as he ages.
